T1  - Advantages and Limitations of an Independent Research Proposal Review System
AU  - Jerdee, Thomas H.
AU  - Rosen, Benson
Y1  - 1977/10/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1977.4406748
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1977.4406748
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 659
EP  - 662
VL  - 2
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the authors examine the high rate of manuscript rejection in the field of management research and offer suggestions on how to improve the quality of management research and the resulting manuscripts. They note that most work that has examined manuscript rejection has focused on the need for more extensive review systems; however, they suggest that inadequately planned research may be a more significant problem. They contend that new mechanisms need to be put in place that would provide researchers with feedback and advice while they are still in the developmental stage of their work. They outline how an independent review system could function to provide this service to researches and discuss some of the potential difficulties and benefits that may arise.
AB  - In this article the authors examine the high rate of manuscript rejection in the field of management research and offer suggestions on how to improve the quality of management research and the resulting manuscripts. They note that most work that has examined manuscript rejection has focused on the need for more extensive review systems; however, they suggest that inadequately planned research may be a more significant problem. They contend that new mechanisms need to be put in place that would provide researchers with feedback and advice while they are still in the developmental stage of their work. They outline how an independent review system could function to provide this service to researches and discuss some of the potential difficulties and benefits that may arise.
